<section xml:id="sec_converse_cp">
  <title>Converse and Contrapositive</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this section,
      we continue our discussion of conditional statements,
      including the converse and contrapositive of a conditional statement.
      The contrapositive provides an alternative proof format for proving that a conditional is true.
      We also introduce biconditional
      (if and only if)
      statements and the proof format for biconditional statements.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_converse">
    <title>\subconv</title>
    <p>
      The statement <m>P \to Q</m> promises that if <m>P</m> is true,
      then <m>Q</m> is also true.
      It does not say the reverse.
      The
      <q>reverse</q>
      might be one of two statements, each of which has a name.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_converse">
      <title>Converse and inverse</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>,
                the <term>converse</term> of <m>P \to Q</m> is <m>Q \to P</m>.
                For example,
                for the statement For all integers <m>s</m>, if <m>s</m> is even,
                then <m>s^2</m> is even. the converse is For all integers <m>s</m>,
                if <m>s^2</m> is even, then <m>s</m> is even.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                In this context, we can translate the conditional <m>P \to Q</m> as
                <q><m>Q</m> <term>if</term> <m>P</m></q>
                and we can translate the converse <m>Q \to P</m> as
                <q><m>Q</m> <term>only if</term> <m>P</m></q>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>,
                the <term>inverse</term> of <m>P \to Q</m> is <m>\neg P \to \neg Q</m>.
                For example,
                for the statement For all integers <m>m</m>, if <m>m</m> is even,
                then <m>m^2</m> is even. the inverse is For all integers <m>m</m>,
                if <m>m</m> is odd, then <m>m^2</m> is odd.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Let's compare the truth table for a conditional statement to its converse.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_converse">
      <title>The converse</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Construct a truth table for a conditional statement and its converse.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We constructed the truth table for the converse in <xref ref="exam_truthtable_compound_conditionals"></xref>.
                    We repeat that here alongside the conditional for comparison in <xref ref="table_truthtable_converse"></xref>.
                    Notice that both a statement and its converse can be true or either can be true with the other false.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <table xml:id="table_truthtable_converse_again">
                  <title>Truth table for a conditional and its converse</title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>P \to Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>Q \to P</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Give an example of a true conditional statement that has a false converse.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Consider the conditional statement If <m>k=3</m>, then <m>k^2 = 9</m>.
                    This statement is true because if <m>k=3</m>, then <m>k^2=3^2=9</m>.
                    The converse is if <m>k^2=9</m>, then <m>k=3</m>.
                    The converse is false because if <m>k=-3</m>,
                    then <m>k^2=(-3)^2=9</m> is true but <m>k=-3=3</m> is false.
                    That is, we have a broken promise <xref ref="thm_broken_promise"/>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_example_true_converse">
              <p>
                Give an example of a true conditional statement that has a true converse.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Consider the conditional statement If <m>n</m> is odd,
                    then <m>n+1</m> is even.
                    The converse is If <m>n+1</m> is even, then <m>n</m> is odd.
                    We proved that both statements are true in <xref ref="sec_even_odd_divides"></xref>
                    <xref ref="exer_prove_consecutive_even_odd"></xref>
                    and again in <xref ref="sec_conditional_statements"></xref>
                    <xref ref="exer_integer_or_next_is_even"></xref>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      When both a conditional statement,
      <m>P \to Q</m>, and its converse,
      <m>Q \to P</m>, are true, we say
      <q><m>P</m> <term>if and only if</term> <m>Q</m></q>. We give a formal definition of the biconditional.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_biconditional">
      <title>Biconditional statements</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>,
                the <term>biconditional</term> statement,
                denoted <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m>,
                is the following compound statement:
                <me>
                  (P \to Q) \land (Q \to P)
                </me>.
                For example, we saw in <xref ref="exam_converse"></xref>
                <xref ref="part_example_true_converse"/> that if <m>P</m>:
                <m>n</m> is odd and <m>Q</m>:
                <m>n+1</m> is even, then <m>P \to Q</m> and <m>Q \to P</m> are true,
                so the biconditional statement <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m> is also true.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The biconditional <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m> is often translated as <m>P</m>
                <term>if and only if</term>
                <m>Q</m> and may also be abbreviated <m>P</m> iff <m>Q</m>.
                For example, when <m>P</m>: <m>n</m> is odd and <m>Q</m>:
                <m>n+1</m> is even, the biconditional
                <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m> says For any integer <m>n</m>,
                <m>n</m> is odd if and only if <m>n+1</m> is even.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Let's construct a truth table for a biconditional statement.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_truthtable_biconditional">
      <title>Truth table of biconditional statement</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/> <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Construct a truth table for a biconditional statement.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We construct the truth table in <xref ref="table_truthtable_biconditional"></xref>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <table xml:id="table_truthtable_biconditional">
                  <title>Truth table for the biconditional <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m></title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>P \to Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>Q \to P</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use this truth table to explain when the biconditional
                <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m> is true and when it is false.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    The biconditional <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m> is true when <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are both true (row 1) or <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are both false
                    (row 4).
                    That is, <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m> is true when <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> have the same truth value meaning <m>P \equiv Q</m>.
                    On the other hand, the biconditional
                    <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m> is false when <m>P</m> is true but <m>Q</m> is false (row 2) or when <m>P</m> is false but <m>Q</m> is true
                    (row 3).
                    That is, <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m> is false when <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> have the opposite truth value meaning <m>Q \equiv \neg P</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Let's practice working with the converse and biconditional statements.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_converse_iff">
      <title>The converse and biconditional statements</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              State the converse of the following statement:
              if the graph <m>G</m> has a vertex of degree five,
              then the graph <m>G</m> has at least six vertices.
              Is the statement true?
              Is the converse true?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_converse_105">
            <p>
              State the converse of the following statement:
              for any integer <m>k</m>, if <m>k >10</m>, then <m>k > 5</m>.
              Is the statement true?
              Is the converse true?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_pos_one">
            <p>
              State the converse of the following statement:
              for any integer <m>t</m>, if <m>t \ge 1</m>, then <m>t >0</m>.
              Is the statement true?
              Is the converse true?
              Hint: <m>t</m> is an integer.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_iff_nsqmult4">
            <p>
              True or false?
              For any integer <m>m</m>, <m>4 \mid m^2</m> if and only if <m>4 \mid m</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_iff_3neven">
            <p>
              True or false?
              For any integer <m>n</m>, <m>n</m> is even if and only if <m>3n</m> is even.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_pff_iff">
    <title>\subpffiff</title>
    <p>
      Since the biconditional is defined as
      <me>
        P \leftrightarrow Q \equiv (P \to Q) \land (Q \to P)
      </me>,
      we can combine the proof formats for
      <q>and</q>
      <xref ref="pff_and"/> with the proof format for a conditional statement <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct"/> to get a new proof format to prove a biconditional statement.
      Normally in
      <q>and</q>
      proofs we begin the two parts with the words
      <q>First</q>
      and
      <q>Second</q>
      (or
      <q>First</q>
      and
      <q>Next</q>).
      In the proof of a biconditional statement,
      the second part proves the converse, so we begin with the word
      <q>Conversely</q>
      instead.
    </p>
    <proof>
    <p>
      <nbsp/> Prove: <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m>
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        First, assume <m>P</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        (Explain why <m>Q</m> is true.)
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus, <m>Q</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Conversely, assume <m>Q</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        (Explain why <m>P</m> is true.)
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus, <m>P</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </proof>
    <p>
      As usual, when we introduce a new proof format,
      we provide an example for you to copy and edit.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_iff_proof">
      <title>Biconditional proof</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Copy the following proof.
              Prove for any integer <m>a</m> that
              <m>a \fn{ mod } 3 = 1</m> if and only if <m>3 \mid (a-1)</m>.
              <em>Proof.</em> Let <m>a</m> be an integer.
              First, assume that <m>a \fn{ mod } 3 = 1</m>.
              By definition of <c>mod</c>,
              it follows that
              <m>a = 3q +1</m> for some integer <m>q</m>.
              Subtracting one from each side of this equation we get <m>a-1 = 3q</m>.
              By definition of divides, it follows that <m>3 \mid (a-1)</m>.
              Conversely, assume that <m>3 \mid (a-1)</m>.
              By definition of divides,
              we can write <m>a-1=3k</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
              Adding one to each side of this equation we get <m>a = 3k+1</m>.
              By definition of <c>mod</c>,
              it follows that <m>a \fn{ mod } 3 = 1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof to prove for any integers <m>a</m> and <m>n</m> that
              <m>a \fn{ mod } n = 1</m> if and only if <m>n \mid (a-1)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      We can now prove the connection between divides and fractions.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_fractions_divides">
      <title>Fractions and Divisibility</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>d</m> and <m>n</m> be integers with <m>d \neq 0</m>.
          Prove that <m>d \mid n</m> exactly when <m>\frac{n}{d}</m> is an integer.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Proof.</em> Let <m>d</m> and <m>n</m> be integers with <m>d \neq 0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          First, assume <m>d \mid n</m>.
          By definition of divides, <m>n=dk</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
          <xref ref="thm_equal_fractions">By</xref>, it follows that
          <me>
            \frac{n}{d} = \frac{dk}{d(1)} = \frac{k}{1} = k
          </me>
          is an integer.
        </p>
        <p>
          Conversely, assume <m>\frac{n}{d}</m> is an integer.
          Say,
          <me>
            \frac{n}{d} = k = \frac{k}{1}
          </me>.
          <xref ref="thm_equal_fractions">By</xref>,
          it follows that <m>n(1) = k(d)</m> or,
          equivalently, <m>n=dk</m>.
          By the definition of divides, <m>d \mid n</m>.
          <m>\Box</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_contrapositive">
    <title>\subcp</title>
    <p>
      While a conditional statement and its converse are not logically equivalent,
      there is a related conditional that is logically equivalent to a conditional.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_contrapositive">
      <title>Contrapositive</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>,
          the <term>contrapositive</term> of the conditional statement <m>P \to Q</m> is the conditional statement <m>\neg Q \to \neg P</m>.
          For example, consider the true statement If <m>k=3</m>,
          then <m>k^2=9</m>. then the contrapositive is If <m>k^2 \neq 9</m>,
          then <m>k \neq 3</m>. which is also true.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Let's explore the logical equivalence of a conditional and its contrapositive.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_equiv_contrapositive">
      <title>Equivalence of statement and its contrapositive</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Construct a truth table of conditional and its contrapositive.
                What do you notice?
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    The truth table is shown in <xref ref="table_truthtable_contrapositive"></xref>.
                    Notice that the columns for the conditional and its contrapositive are identical.
                    That means that a conditional and its contrapositive are logically equivalent.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <table xml:id="table_truthtable_contrapositive">
                  <title>Truth table for the contrapositive</title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>P \to Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\neg Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\neg P</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\neg Q \to \neg P</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Explain in words why the contrapositive is logically equivalent to the original conditional.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Think about what makes the conditional <m>P \to Q</m> is true.
                    We are promising that if <m>P</m> is true, then <m>Q</m> is true.
                    What happens if <m>\neg Q</m> is true?
                    That means <m>Q</m> is false and so <m>P</m> cannot be true
                    (or we would break our promise)
                    and so <m>P</m> must be false which means <m>\neg P</m> is true.
                    That is, if <m>\neg Q</m>, then <m>\neg P</m>,
                    which is the contrapositive.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      We add the contrapositive to our list of logical equivalences.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_cp">
      <title>Contraposition equivalence</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>,
          <me>
            (P \to Q) \equiv (\neg Q \to \neg P)
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      Let's practice working with the contrapositive.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_cp">
      <title>Contrapositive</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Write the contrapositive of the true statement: For all integers <m>n</m>,
              if <m>n>10</m>, then <m>n>5</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Write the contrapositive of the true statement: For all graphs <m>G</m>,
              if <m>G</m> has at most five vertices,
              then <m>G</m> has at most 10 edges.
              Hint: To negate
              <q>at more</q>
              use
              <q>more than</q>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_cp_nsqodd_nodd">
            <p>
              Write the contrapositive of the true statement: For all integers <m>n</m>,
              if <m>n^2</m> is odd, then <m>n</m> is odd.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_cp_easier">
            <p>
              Which statement do you think would be easier to prove:
              the statement from <xref ref="part_cp_nsqodd_nodd"/> or its contrapositive?
              Explain.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_pff_cp">
    <title>\subpffcp</title>
    <p>
      Since a conditional and its contrapositive are logically equivalent,
      we have a new way to prove <m>P \to Q</m>:
      we can prove its contrapositive <m>\neg Q \to \neg P</m> instead.
    </p>
    <proof>
    <p>
      Prove: <m>P \to Q</m>
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        We will prove the contrapositive, namely
        (fill in <m>\neg Q \to \neg P</m>).
      </p>
      <p>
        Assume <m>\neg Q</m> is true.
      </p>
      <p>
        (Explain why it follows that <m>\neg P</m> is true.)
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus <m>\neg P</m> is true.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </proof>
    <p>
      Let's do an example with this new proof format.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_direct_proof_ifnsqoddthennodd">
      <title>Contrapositive proof if <m>n^2</m> is odd, then <m>n</m> is also odd</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_ifnsqoddthennodd">
            <p>
              Perhaps you noticed in <xref ref="act_cp"></xref>
              <xref ref="part_cp_easier"/> that the contrapositive would be easier to prove.
              Copy the following proof.
              Prove for any integer <m>n</m>,
              if <m>n^2</m> is odd then <m>n</m> is odd.
              <proof>
                <p>
                  Let <m>n</m> be an integer.
                  We will prove the contrapositive,
                  namely that if <m>n</m> is even, then <m>n^2</m> is even.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Assume that <m>n</m> is even.
                  By the definition of even,
                  we can write <m>n=2k</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
                  Then
                  <me>
                    n^2=(2k)^2=(2k)(2k) = (2)(2)kk = 4k^2 = 2(2k^2)
                  </me>.
                  Since <m>2k^2</m> is an integer,
                  it follows from the definition of even that <m>n^2</m> is even.
                </p>
              </proof>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof to prove for any integer <m>n</m> if <m>5n</m> is odd,
              then <m>n</m> is odd.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      When a proof by contradiction does not use the supposed hypothesis until the ending contradiction,
      we can often rewrite the proof using the contrapositive,
      avoiding the proof by contradiction.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_product_even_implies_even_factor">
      <title>Rewriting a proof by contradiction using the contrapositive</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_contradiction_product_even_implies_even_factor">
              <p>
                Read the following proof by contradiction.
                Prove that for any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> if <m>ab</m> is even,
                then <m>a</m> is even or <m>b</m> is even.
                <proof>
                  <p>
                    Suppose not.
                    Then for some integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> we would have that <m>ab</m> is even but neither <m>a</m> nor <m>b</m> is even.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    First, since neither <m>a</m> nor <m>b</m> is even,
                    that means <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are odd.
                    By the definition of odd,
                    we can write <m>a = 2k_1+1</m> and
                    <m>b = 2k_2+1</m> for some integers <m>k_1</m> and <m>k_2</m>.
                    Multiplying <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> we get
                    <me>
                      ab=(2k_1+1)(2k_2+1)=4k_1k_2+2k_1+2k_2+1 = 2(2k_1k_2 + k_1 + k_2) + 1
                    </me>
                    and so <m>ab</m> is odd.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    On the other hand, we said <m>ab</m> was even.
                    This is a contradiction.
                  </p>
                </proof>
                What are the contradictory statements <m>Q</m> and <m>\neg Q</m>?
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    The contradictory statements are <m>Q: ab</m> is odd and <m>\neg Q: ab</m> is even.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                State the contrapositive of the statement
                <q>For any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> if <m>ab</m> is even,
                then <m>a</m> is even or <m>b</m> is even.</q>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    By DeMorgan's Laws <xref ref="thm_demorgans"/>,
                    the negation of the conclusion <m>a</m> is even or <m>b</m> is even. is the statement <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are odd.
                    The contrapositive is For any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                    if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are odd, then <m>ab</m> is odd.
                    Notice that we keep the universal quantifier.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Adapt the proof from <xref ref="part_contradiction_product_even_implies_even_factor"/> to prove for any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> if <m>ab</m> is even,
                then either <m>a</m> is even or <m>b</m> is even using the contrapositive <xref ref="pff_if_then_cp"/>.
                Hint: you should not have to change much of the proof.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Prove: for any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> if <m>ab</m> is even,
                    then either <m>a</m> is even or <m>b</m> is even.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <em>Proof.</em> We will prove the contrapositive,
                    namely for any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                    if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are odd, then <m>ab</m> is odd.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be odd integers.
                    By the definition of odd,
                    we can write <m>a = 2k_1+1</m> and
                    <m>b = 2k_2+1</m> for some integers <m>k_1</m> and <m>k_2</m>.
                    Multiplying <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> we get
                    <me>
                      ab=(2k_1+1)(2k_2+1)=4k_1k_2+2k_1+2k_2+1 = 2(2k_1k_2 + k_1 + k_2) + 1
                    </me>
                    and so <m>ab</m> is odd.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_converse">for</xref> \subconv</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_converse_TorF_lessthan">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the statement: for any real number <m>x</m>,
            if <m>x^2 \le 100</m>, then <m>x \le 10</m>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Is the statement true or false?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  State the converse.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Give a counterexample to show that the converse is false.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_converse_TorF_divides">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the statement: for all integers <m>n</m>,
            if <m>6 \mid n</m>, then <m>3 \mid n</m>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Is the statement true or false?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  State the converse.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Give a counterexample to show that the converse is false.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_converse_TorF_mod">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the statement: for any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
            if <m>a \fn{ mod } 5 = b \fn{ mod } 5</m>,
            then <m>a^2 \fn{ mod } 5 = b^2 \fn{ mod } 5</m>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Is the statement true or false?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  State the converse.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Give a counterexample to show that the converse is false.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_converse_inverse_equiv">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use a truth table to show that the converse <m>Q \to P</m> and the inverse
            <m>\neg P \to \neg Q</m> are logically equivalent.
            Include intermediate columns for <m>\neg P</m> and <m>\neg Q</m>.
            This result helps explain why we rarely discuss the inverse.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_TorF_iff">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Decide if each biconditional statement
            (from <xref ref="act_converse_iff"></xref>)
            is true or false.
            Explain briefly.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any integers <m>k</m>, <m>k>10</m> if and only if <m>k>5</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any integer <m>n</m>, <m>n</m> is even if and only if <m>3n</m> is even.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any integer <m>m</m>, <m>4 \mid m^2</m> if and only if <m>4 \mid m</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_neg_biconditional">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Construct a truth table for <m>\neg(P \leftrightarrow Q)</m>.
                  Hint: Copy the truth table from <xref ref="exam_truthtable_biconditional"></xref>
                  and add one additional column.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The negation <m>\neg(P \leftrightarrow Q)</m> is logically equivalent to a simpler statement.
                  What is it?
                  Hint: <xref ref="table_truthtable_xor"></xref>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_converse_iff">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the converse of <m>P \to Q</m> is?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to find examples to show that <m>P \to Q</m> and its converse are not equivalent?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How the biconditional statement <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m> is defined?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  When a biconditional statement is true and when it is false?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_pff_iff">for</xref> \subpffiff</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_iff_even">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="pff_iff">Use</xref> to prove that <m>n</m> is even if and only if <m>n+3</m> is odd,
            for any integer <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_iff_solution">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="pff_iff">Use</xref> to prove that <m>2n-7=5</m> if and only if <m>n =6</m> for any integer <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_pff_iff">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to format the proof of a biconditional statement?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why the second part of the proof of a biconditional statement begins with the word
                  <q>Conversely</q>?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_contrapositive">for</xref> \subcp</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_cp_assorted">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write the contrapositive of each statement.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any real number <m>x</m>,
                  if <m>3x \le 6</m>, then <m>x \le 2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any integer <m>s</m>, if <m>s^2</m> is even, then <m>s</m> is even.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For all graphs <m>G</m>,
                  if <m>G</m> has at least 5 vertices,
                  then <m>G</m> must have at least 5 edges.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_subgraph_acyclic">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>H</m> be a subgraph of a graph <m>G</m>.
            Consider the statement If <m>G</m> is acyclic, then <m>H</m> is acyclic.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  State the contrapositive of this statement and explain why it's true.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Explain why it follows that this statement is true.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_cp_irrat">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write the contrapositive of each statement.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For all real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
                  if <m>x</m> is rational and <m>y</m> is irrational,
                  then <m>x+y</m> is irrational.
                  Note: from <xref ref="defn_sets_of_real_numbers"></xref>
                  rational and irrational are negations.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For all real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
                  if <m>x+y</m> is irrational,
                  then either <m>x</m> is irrational or <m>y</m> is irrational.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For all real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
                  if <m>x+y</m> is rational,
                  then <m>x</m> is rational and <m>y</m> is rational.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_cp">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the contrapositive of <m>P \to Q</m> is?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why a conditional statement and its contrapositive are equivalent?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use a truth table to verify that a conditional statement and its contrapositive are logically equivalent?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_pff_cp">for</xref> \subpffcp</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_sq_even_implies_even">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the contrapositive <xref ref="pff_if_then_cp"/> to prove that for any integer <m>s</m>,
            if <m>s^2</m> is even then <m>s</m> is even.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_3m_odd">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the contrapositive <xref ref="pff_if_then_cp"/> to prove for any integer <m>m</m>,
            if <m>3m</m> is odd, then <m>m</m> is odd.
            (We proved the converse in <xref ref="act_pffifthen"></xref>
            <xref ref="part_if_then_direct"/>.)
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prove_only_check_prime_divisors">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In this exercise we <xref ref="thm_show_is_prime">prove</xref>
            <xref ref="part_only_check_prime_divisors"/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Use the contrapositive <xref ref="pff_if_then_cp"/> to prove that for any integers <m>n</m>,
            <m>p</m>,
            and <m>m</m>, if <m>p \nmid n</m>, then <m>mp \nmid n</m>.
            Note that this statement can be rephrased as if <m>p</m> is not a divisor of <m>n</m>,
            then no multiple of <m>p</m> is a divisor of <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prove_only_check_to_sqrtn">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In this exercise we <xref ref="thm_show_is_prime">prove</xref>
            <xref ref="part_only_check_to_sqrtn"/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Prove for any integers <m>a</m>,
            <m>b</m>, and <m>n</m>, if <m>ab=n</m>,
            then <m>a \le \sqrt{n}</m> or <m>b \le \sqrt{n}</m>.
            Hint: Prove the contrapositive <xref ref="pff_if_then_cp"/>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_pff_cp">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to prove a conditional statement by proving the contrapositive instead?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  When we want to prove the contrapositive instead of the original conditional statement?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What we can write in a proof using the contrapositive so that the reader knows we are using the contrapositive?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_iff_using_cp_evens">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="pff_iff">Use</xref> to prove that <m>m</m> is odd if and only if <m>m^3</m> is odd.
            Hint: Use the contrapositive <xref ref="pff_if_then_cp"/> for the converse
            (second part).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="part_prove_sqrtp_irrat">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Copy the following proof by contradiction that <m>\sqrt(2)</m> is irrational,
            being sure to figure out why each statement is true.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Suppose not.
            Then <m>\sqrt{2}</m> is rational.
            By the definition of rational <xref ref="defn_sets_of_real_numbers"/>, we can write
            <me>
              \sqrt{2} = \frac{s}{t}
            </me>
            for some positive integers <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> with <m>t \neq 0</m>.
            <xref ref="thm_equal_fractions">By</xref>,
            we may assume that we have canceled any common factors so that <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> are coprime.
          </p>
          <p>
            On the other hand,
            multiply each side of this equation by <m>t</m> to get
            <me>
              s = \sqrt{2}t
            </me>.
            Square each side of this equation to get
            <me>
              s^2=2t^2
            </me>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Thus, <m>s^2</m> is even.
            <xref ref="exer_proof_sq_even_implies_even">By</xref>,
            it follows that <m>s</m> is even.
            By definition of even,
            we can write <m>s = 2k</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
            Substituting in we get
            <me>
              (2k)^2 = 2t^2
            </me>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Simplifying we get <m>t^2=2k^2</m>.
            Thus, <m>t^2</m> is also even.
            <xref ref="exer_proof_sq_even_implies_even">By</xref>,
            it follows that <m>t</m> is also even.
            Since <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> are even,
            it follows that two is a common divisor of <m>s</m> and <m>t</m>.
            Thus, <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> are not coprime.
          </p>
          <p>
            This is a contradiction.
            Thus <m>\sqrt{2}</m> is irrational.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
