      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_TorF_iff"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: One direction is true, but the other direction is false.
            Find a counterexample.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: It is true.
            Check both directions.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: One direction is true, but the other direction is false.
            Find a counterexample.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_iff_even"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        <xref ref="pff_iff">Use</xref> to prove that <m>n</m> is even if and only if <m>n+3</m> is odd,
        for any integer <m>n</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_iff_solution"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Here is an outline of the proof.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <em>Proof.</em>  Let <m>n</m> be an integer.
        First, assume <m>n</m> is even.  By definition of even we can write <m>n=</m> \ldots.  Then
        <me>
          n+3 = \ldots = 2k'+1
        </me>
        where <m>k' = \ldots</m> is an integer.  Thus <m>n+3</m> is odd.
        Next, assume <m>n+3</m> is odd.  By definition of odd we can write <m>n+3=</m> \ldots.  Then
        <me>
          n = \ldots = 2k'
        </me>
        where <m>k' = \ldots</m> is an integer.  Thus <m>n</m> is even.
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        Hint: Here is an outline of the proof.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <em>Proof.</em>  Let <m>n</m> be an integer.
        First, assume <m>2n-7=5</m>.  Then, \ldots.  Thus <m>n=6</m>.
        Next, assume <m>n=6</m>.  Then, <m>2n-7 = 2(6)-7 = \ldots</m>.
      </blockquote>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_cp_assorted"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            For any real number <m>x</m>,
            if <m>x > 2</m>, then <m>3x > 6</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The negation of even is odd.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The negation of
            <q>at least</q>
            is
            <q>fewer than</q>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_subgraph_acyclic"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The negation of
            <q>acyclic</q>
            is
            <q>contains a cycle.</q>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>H</m> contains a subgraph <m>C</m> that is a cycle,
            then <m>C</m> is a subgraph of <m>G</m> and so <m>G</m> contains a cycle.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_cp_irrat"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hints: First,
        <q>rational</q>
        and
        <q>irrational</q>
        are negations.
        Also, use DeMorgan's laws any time you need to negate a statement involving
        <q>and</q>
        or
        <q>or</q>.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Hint: The contrapositive begins
              <q>For all real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
              if <m>x+y</m> is rational, then <ellipsis/></q>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Hint: Your answer should include the word
              <q>and</q>. It should not include the word
              <q>irrational</q>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Hint: Your answer should not include the word
              <q>rational</q>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_3m_odd"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Here is an outline of the proof.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <em>Proof.</em> Let <m>m</m> be an integer.  We will prove the contrapositive, namely \ldots.
        Assume, \ldots.  Then, \ldots.  Thus, \ldots.  <m>\Box</m>
      </blockquote>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_only_check_prime_divisors"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Here is an outline of the proof.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <em>Proof.</em> Let <m>n</m>, <m>p</m>, and <m>m</m> be integers.  We will prove the contrapositive, namely if <m>mp \mid n</m>, then <m>p \mid n</m>.
        Assume, <m>mp \mid n</m>.  Then, by definition of divides we can write <m>n= \ldots = pk</m> where <m>k=\ldots</m> is an integer.  Thus, <m>p \mid n</m>.  <m>\Box</m>
      </blockquote>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_only_check_to_sqrtn"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Use DeMorgan's laws.
        Recall that <m>\sqrt{n}\sqrt{n} = n</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_iff_using_cp_evens"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: First, prove if <m>m</m> is odd, then <m>m^3</m> is odd.
        Conversely, prove the contrapositive of the converse,
        namely if <m>m</m> is even, then <m>m^3</m> is even.
        Another hint:
        <m>(2k+1)^3 = (2k+1)(2k+1)(2k+1) = (4k^2+4k+1)(2k+1)=\ldots</m>
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
</section>